    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our lineup leans heavily on high-efficiency matchups against favorable pitching rotations. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (76.21) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) anchor the roster, benefitting from advantageous matchups against Martin and Buehler, respectively. **Vinnie Pasquantino** is our highest-projected asset, leveraging a significant 17% SP skill boost and a prime #3 spot in the order, though we must keep a close eye on the 31% rain risk that could threaten his plate appearances. Meanwhile, **Mickey Moniak** earns his spot through a combination of a soft 5.19 xERA matchup and a massive 14% boost for his platoon advantage, coupled with the high-upside potential of facing a slow-delivery pitcher that plays right into our focus on stolen base efficiency. **Brice Turang** (73.40) also earns a premium start, as his top-of-the-order positioning and the 19% SP skill advantage against Irvin make him a lock for daily production.\n\nThe decision to keep **Kyle Karros** (50.14) and **Max Muncy** (50.10) on the bench was a razor-thin margin, with both players finishing just points behind the bottom of our active lineup. **Kyle Karros** was hampered significantly by his assumed #9 spot in the batting order, which dragged down an otherwise high-upside matchup against Buehler. While **Max Muncy** possesses the pedigree to outperform his current projection, he remains benched due to a lack of platoon leverage and an unfavorable spot in the order that creates too much risk for our limited game caps. We are also monitoring the status of **Dalton Rushing** and **Alex Freeland**; while both currently project as strong starts due to wind-assisted park factors and favorable matchups against Kumar Rocker, their statuses remain \"Lineup Pending.\" Should the official lineups force them lower in the order than our current assumptions, we may reconsider our middle-infield configuration to ensure we aren't wasting caps on low-leverage spots.",
